## 🧪 User Psychology & Behavioral Design

### 1. Hick's Law (Choices → Decision Time)

**"Decision time increases logarithmically with the number of choices."**

**Implications:**
```tsx
❌ BAD: 15 buttons in a toolbar
<Toolbar>
  <Button>New</Button>
  <Button>Open</Button>
  <Button>Save</Button>
  <Button>Export</Button>
  <Button>Import</Button>
  <Button>Print</Button>
  <Button>Share</Button>
  {/* ... 8 more buttons */}
</Toolbar>

✅ GOOD: Group into 3-5 primary actions + overflow menu
<Toolbar>
  <Button>New</Button>
  <Button>Save</Button>
  <Button>Share</Button>
  <DropdownMenu>
    <Button>More</Button>
    <Menu>
      <Item>Export</Item>
      <Item>Import</Item>
      <Item>Print</Item>
      {/* ... */}
    </Menu>
  </DropdownMenu>
</Toolbar>
```

### 2. Fitts's Law (Size & Distance → Interaction Time)

**"Time to reach a target = function of distance and size."**

**Implications:**

**Touch Targets (Mobile):**
```
Minimum: 44x44px (Apple HIG, WCAG 2.2)
Recommended: 48x48px (Material Design)
Optimal: 56x56px (easy one-handed use)
```

**Proximity (Place related actions close):**
```tsx
✅ GOOD: Action buttons near content
<TaskCard>
  <TaskTitle />
  <TaskMeta />
  {/* Actions right here, not far away */}
  <div className="flex gap-2 mt-4">
    <button>Edit</button>
    <button>Delete</button>
  </div>
</TaskCard>
```

### 3. Jakob's Law (Familiarity → Usability)

**"Users spend most of their time on OTHER sites. They expect yours to work the same way."**

**Follow Conventions:**
- Logo in top-left (links to home)
- Search in top-right
- Hamburger menu for mobile navigation
- Double-click to edit inline
- Ctrl+S to save, Ctrl+Z to undo
- Swipe to delete (mobile)

**Don't Reinvent:**
```tsx
✅ Standard date picker (users know how to use it)
<input type="date" />

❌ Custom date picker with unusual interaction
<CustomWeirdDatePicker /> {/* Users need to learn new pattern */}
```

### 4. Zeigarnik Effect (Incomplete Tasks → Mental Tension)

**"People remember uncompleted tasks better than completed ones."**

**Implications:**

**Progress Indicators:**
```tsx
<div className="mb-6">
  <div className="flex justify-between text-sm mb-2">
    <span className="font-medium">Profile Setup</span>
    <span className="text-slate-600">3 of 5 completed</span>
  </div>
  <div className="h-2 bg-slate-200 dark:bg-slate-700 rounded-full overflow-hidden">
    <div className="h-full bg-gradient-button-primary w-3/5 transition-all duration-500" />
  </div>
</div>
```

**Show What's Left:**
```tsx
<Checklist>
  <Item checked>✓ Add profile photo</Item>
  <Item checked>✓ Set display name</Item>
  <Item checked>✓ Choose theme</Item>
  <Item>⭘ Connect calendar (optional)</Item>
  <Item>⭘ Invite team members (optional)</Item>
</Checklist>
```

### 5. Peak-End Rule (Users Remember Peaks & Endings)

**"Overall experience is judged by peaks (best/worst moments) and endings."**

**Design Implications:**

**Create Peaks (Delightful Moments):**
```tsx
// Confetti on task completion
const handleComplete = () => {
  completeTask(taskId);
  confetti({
    particleCount: 100,
    spread: 70,
    origin: { y: 0.6 },
  });
};
```

**End on High Note:**
```tsx
// Success screen after onboarding
<div className="text-center py-12">
  <motion.div
    initial={{ scale: 0 }}
    animate={{ scale: 1 }}
    transition={{ type: "spring", stiffness: 200 }}
  >
    <Check className="w-24 h-24 mx-auto text-success-500" />
  </motion.div>
  <h1 className="mt-6 text-3xl font-bold">You're all set!</h1>
  <p className="mt-2 text-slate-600">Your workspace is ready to go.</p>
  <button className="mt-8 btn-primary btn-lg">
    Start Creating
  </button>
</div>
```

